{"id":"2209.13898","submitter":"Pawan Kumar Mishra","authors":"Ajeya Krishna, Pawan Kumar Mishra, and Shradha Mishra","title":"Active Brownian particles can mimic the pattern of the substrate","comments":null,"journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"cond-mat.soft cond-mat.stat-mech","license":"http://creativecommons.org/publicdomain/zero/1.0/","abstract":"  Active Brownian particles (ABPs) are termed out to be a successful way of\nmodeling the moving microorganism on the substrate. In recent studies it is\nshown that such organism can sense the characteristics of substrate. Motivated\nwith such work we studied the dynamics and the steady state of ABP moving on a\nsubstrate with space dependent activity. On the substrate some regions are\nmarked as high in activity and other regions are such that, particles behave as\npassive Brownian particle. The system is studied in one and two dimensions with\nGaussian and uniform distribution of activity profile on the substrate.\nAlthough the microscopic dynamics of ABPs does not involve any alignment\ninteraction but inhomogeneous activity lead to formation of ordered structure\nand current along the interface of the activity profile. The whole interface of\nthe activity profile is divided symmetrically in two regions. The two regions\nhave current in two opposite directions in one-dimensional system and two\nvortices of opposite helicity in two-dimensions. This lead to the flow of\nparticles from the active region to the passive region. The final steady state\nof particle density profile very much follow the struture of the inhomogeneous\nactivity. Further we check the steady state density profile for various\ndifferent shapes and structure on two-dimensional substrate. Hence the\ncollection of ABPs on inhomogeneous substrate can mimic the inomogeneity of the\nsubstrate.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Wed, 28 Sep 2022 07:53:35 GMT"}],"update_date":"2022-09-29"}
